Consider a point P=(a,b) on the curve where b=y(a). The tangent line
through this point will go through (a,b) and have slope y'(a) where y'
is the derivative. Therefore the tangent line L(x) will satisfy

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}L(x)=y'(a)(x-a)+y(a).\end{align*}

We know that y=1/x and so

\begin{align*}y(a)=\frac{1}{a}.\end{align*}

Next we calculate the derivative:

\begin{align*}y'  = -\frac{1}{x^2}\end{align*}

and plugging in the point x=a we get

\begin{align*}y'(a) = -\frac{1}{a^2}.\end{align*}

Up to this point we have enough information to compute the tangent line
for any point x=a on the curve. However, we are looking for the two
points where the slope is parallel (therefore equal) to -100, the slope
of the line given in the question. This gives the equation:

\begin{align*}-\frac{1}{a^2} = -100\end{align*}

Solving for a, we get

\begin{align*}a = \pm \frac{1}{10}.\end{align*}

Therefore, we need to find the equation of the tangent line where
\emph{a = -1/10} and \emph{a = 1/10}.

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  When \emph{a = -1/10},
\end{itemize}

\begin{align*}y(a) = y(-1/10) = \frac{1}{-1/10} = -10\end{align*}

and the slope is $m = -100$ (because the lines are parallel). Therefore,
the equation of the tangent line is

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}L(x) = -100(x - (-1/10)) + (-10)\end{align*}

This is a sufficient answer, but if you simplify to \emph{y=mx + b}
form, you find instead that \emph{L(x) = -100x -20}.

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  When \emph{a = 1/10},
\end{itemize}

\begin{align*}y(a) = y(-1/10) = \frac{1}{1/10} = 10,\end{align*}

with slope $m = -100$. Therefore, the equation of the tangent line is

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}L(x) = -100(x - 1/10) + 10.\end{align*}

This is a sufficient answer, but if you simplify to \emph{y=mx + b}
form, you find \emph{L(x) = -100x +20}

hints:
Consider a generic point $P = (a,b)$ on the given curve. What is the
slope of the tangent line at the point $x=a$? (Your solution should be a
function of $a$.)
